{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565051"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:22:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:22:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17195"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17195"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.03,0.3,0.4,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9885"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110569"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9885"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17195"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92830"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"6626"},{"type":"tags","id":"7888"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41722"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110569"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman of Chinese descent presents to the General Practice clinic concerned about gradually developing patches of pigmentation on her face over the past two years. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as an accountant and denies excessive sun exposure. She is particularly worried about skin cancer as her parent had melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are symmetrical blue-grey patches on bilaterally over her malar regions and temples. The patches are flat, clustered together and non-tender with well- defined borders. There is no involvement of the oral mucosa or sclera.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Naevus of Ota","Post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation","Melasma","Acquired naevus of Ota-like macules (Hori\u0027s naevus)","Solar lentigo"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents with the classic features of acquired naevus of Ota-like macules (ABNOM), also known as Hori\u0027s naevus. The key diagnostic features include bilateral blue-grey patches appearing in adulthood, particularly in Asian women, with a predilection for the malar regions, temples, eyelids, and ala nasi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcquired naevus of Ota-like macules\u003C/strong\u003E typically develops in the third or fourth decade of life and is characterised by bilateral, symmetrical, blue-grey patches on the face. Unlike naevus of Ota, it does not involve the mucous membranes or sclera and appears later in life. Diagnosis is clinical though biopsy can show bipolar irregularly shaped melanocytes in the upper dermis.  The lesions tend to have well-defined borders and cluster together which helps differentiate from melasma which have ill-defined borders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaevus of Ota\u003C/strong\u003E is typically unilateral not bilateral, present at birth or develops in early childhood up less commonly in mid 20s, and often involves the sclera and oral mucosa. The distribution typically follows the first and second branches of the trigeminal nerve. It is also blue-black or grey patches with brown and small spots. Rarely in 10% of cases it is bilateral. It has an increased risk of glaucoma and uveal melanoma so differentiation is important. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelasma\u003C/strong\u003E presents as brown or grey-brown patches with well-defined borders rather than blue-grey patches though also more common in people of Asian background. It is typically more pronounced with sun exposure and has a predilection for the cheeks, forehead, and upper lip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-inflammatory hyperpigmentation\u003C/strong\u003E occurs following inflammation or injury to the skin and would have a clear preceding event. The colour is typically brown rather than blue-grey.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESolar lentigo\u003C/strong\u003E presents as well-defined brown macules in sun-exposed areas and is usually multiple small spots rather than presenting as patches. They are more common in older individuals with significant cumulative sun exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acquired naevus of Ota-like macules (ABNOM) typically presents as bilateral blue-grey patches on the face in adult Asian women.","ABNOM is distinguished from naevus of Ota by its bilateral distribution, later age of onset, and lack of mucosal involvement.","The diagnosis of ABNOM is clinical and does not require biopsy in typical cases."],"references":["Lee WJ, Lee GY, Won KH, Won CH, Lee MW, Choi JH, Chang SE. Comparison of acquired bilateral nevus of Ota-like macules in men and women. Indian Journal of Dermatology, Venereology and Leprology. 2014;80:313-319.  Available at: https://ijdvl.com/comparison-of-acquired-bilateral-nevus-of-ota-like-macules-in-men-and-women/","Park JH, Lee MH. Acquired, bilateral nevus of Ota-like macules (ABNOM) associated with Ota\u0027s nevus: case report. J Korean Med Sci. 2004 Aug;19(4):616-8.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2816902/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92830"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17195"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92830"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-01T18:12:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-01T18:14:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9885"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110569"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their d